.TH STRSPLITS 1 "2026-03-04" "strsplit 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
strsplit \- split input strings by delimiter and print each item on separate line
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B strsplit
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] [\fIARGS\fR...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B strsplit
splits input string(s) by a delimiter and prints each item as a separate line.
.PP
If \fIARGS\fR are provided, each argument is treated as one input line (one run).
.PP
If no argument is specified, input is read from stdin, line by line (each line is one run).
.PP
For each run:
.RS
.IP 1. 3
Take input string
.IP 2. 3
Optionally case-fold
.IP 3. 3
Split by delimiter (default: whitespace \\s+)
.IP 4. 3
Optionally sort
.IP 5. 3
Print items according to format rules
.RE
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-delim " \fIREGEX\fR
Use POSIX Extended Regular Expression as delimiter. Default: \fB\\s+\fR
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-linenum
Print line number before each split item. Default numbering base: 1
.TP
.BR \-0 ", " \-\-0\-based
Use 0-based numbering
.TP
.BR \-z ", " \-\-reset
Reset numbering between runs. Default behavior: if multiple runs and \fB\-z\fR not
specified, numbering continues across runs
.TP
.BR \-c ", " \-\-format " \fIFMT\fR
Custom output format. If \fB\-n\fR is enabled, default format: \fB"%d. %s"\fR.
If \fB\-n\fR is not enabled, default format: \fB"%s"\fR.
.br
Format placeholders: \fB%d\fR = item index, \fB%s\fR = item string
.TP
.BR \-N ", " \-\-insert\-nl
Insert one blank line between runs. May be specified repeatedly:
\fB\-N\fR = 1 blank line, \fB\-NN\fR = 2 blank lines, etc.
No trailing blank lines after last run
.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-indented
Indent output by 2 spaces per level. Repeatable: \fB\-i\fR = 2 spaces, \fB\-ii\fR = 4 spaces
.TP
.BR \-r ", " \-\-reversed
Reverse final ordering
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-ignore\-case
Case-insensitive lexicographic sort
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-numeric\-sort
Compare using strtol()
.TP
.BR \-g ", " \-\-general\-numeric\-sort
Compare using strtod()
.TP
.BR \-H ", " \-\-human\-numeric\-sort
Human numeric sort (e.g., 2K < 10K)
.TP
.BR \-D ", " \-\-dictionary\-sort
Compare ignoring non-alphanumeric chars
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version\-sort
Version-aware sort (e.g., 1.9 < 1.10)
.TP
.BR \-? ", " \-\-help
Show help message
.SH SORTING
Sorting applies after splitting and before printing. If multiple sort modes are
specified, the last one wins. If no sort option is specified, original order is preserved.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
Invalid arguments
.TP
.B 2
Runtime error
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic split
.RS
.nf
$ strsplit "foo bar baz"
foo
bar
baz
.fi
.RE
.SS With numbering (0-based) and reset
.RS
.nf
$ strsplit -z0niN 'foo bar' 'cat dog'
  0. foo
  1. bar

  0. cat
  1. dog
.fi
.RE
.SS Numeric sort
.RS
.nf
$ strsplit -sn "10 2 30 4"
1. 2
2. 4
3. 10
4. 30
.fi
.RE
.SS Version sort
.RS
.nf
$ strsplit -V "1.2 1.10 1.3"
1.2
1.3
1.10
.fi
.RE
.SS Read from stdin
.RS
.nf
$ echo "foo bar baz" | strsplit
foo
bar
baz
.fi
.RE
